courses.learning_outcomes:
This course aims at enabling non-technical students to develop a comprehensive understanding on the energy crisis and environmental issues. Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
identify the seriousness of energy crisis in 21st century. They will recognize the energy options we have and compare their impacts on the environment;
analyze the scientific debates on the nature, causes, and consequences of global warming. Students will illustrate the complexity of environmental issues our society is currently facing;
recognize essential components to develop a green society;
evaluate the local and global development from a comprehensive point of view.

This course is built around the fundamental understanding of basic principles, techniques, and applications of AI. The cornerstone of this course involves evaluation of AI systems in our daily lives and exploring potential solutions with AI and machine learning technologies. Upon successful completion of the course, students shall be able to achieve the following outcomes:
explain the basic concepts and major elements of today's AI technology;
understand and use the basic terminology of AI;
describe the basic types of tasks that an AI system can accomplish;
explain the operation of major applications of AI;
suggest possible new use cases of AI;
explain the role of data in AI;
describe the workflow for AI application development.

Students should be able to achieve the following at the end of the course:
Understand the situation of nature conservation in Hong Kong;
Describe and explain concepts and principles of nature conservation in local and global context;
Able to explain how protecting marine and country parks contributes to biodiversity conservation, geodiversity conservation and the sustainable use of natural resources;
Explore the process in the formation of local nature conservation policy and practices;
Understand the role of conservation policies and practices in promoting environmental sustainability and achieving the SDGs;
Appreciate and differentiate values and benefits of protected areas to the community;
Identify viable measures in conserving habitats and ecosystems in Hong Kong; and
Analyze strengths and weaknesses of various conservation measures applied in Hong Kong.

1) To comprehend knowledge of China’s main environmental issues, environmental governance, key policies and international commitments as well as main global environmental issues and related political debates/controversies;
2) To train integrative skills to apply political, public policy and scientific analysis to explain the causes, impacts and solutions of China’s environmental crises and the linkages across different geographic scales;
3) To establish the value to become responsible global citizens and contribute to the achievement of Sustainable Development Goals.

1. Have basic understanding of remote sensing technology;
2. Acquire preliminary skills of image interpretation;
3. Understand the local, regional and global applications of remote sensing that link with sustainability; and
4. Acknowledge the impact of the spatial information technology on the society and in daily life.

After taking this course, students are expected to:
develop a general understanding of the causes and consequences of extreme natural events;
appreciate the impacts on the lives and properties of people around the world;
gain basic knowledge of geological, meteorological and hydrological hazards;
learn how environmental risk arises from the complex interaction between the physical environment and human society;
understand the challenges and potential calamities posed by natural hazards;
apply various techniques in natural hazard management contributing to sustainable development;
learn how to assess and manage the risks associated with natural hazards (specific to SDG11); and
learn about sustainable practices that can reduce the vulnerability of communities to natural hazards (specific to SDG13)

By the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:
Understand the concepts and explain the formation of different natural landscapes, landforms and phenomena across the planet;
Understand the inter-relationships between different physical and human-induced processes in shaping natural landscapes and landforms in the terrestrial and marine environments;
Assess the impacts of climate change on natural wonders, and evaluate different options of climate change mitigation and adaptation
Identify the challenges faced by the world’s natural wonders, and develop sustainable solutions in their preservation and management; and
Improve academic skills in critical thinking, researching, teamwork, presentation, essay editing and writing.

After taking this course, students will be able to:
1. describe and compare the major principles and practices of modern agriculture and those of permaculture;
2. analyse the ethical issues related to modern agriculture in contemporary societies;
3. formulate personal views on how to live more ethically with nature.

After completing the course, students should be able to
• recall and understand the basic idea and steps of how life comes into being in the astronomical perspective;
• demonstrate their understanding of the relationship between various component topics of astrobiology;
• form their opinion of the implication of the scientific knowledge of the origin of life on human’s position in the universe and the history of the universe;
• gain intellectual perspectives and appreciation on the development of the astrobiology field in particular, and the multidisciplinary study of problem in general;
• understand the basic principles of scientific method through examples.

Students will be expected to
- comprehend, analyze, and apply some general knowledge of astronomy, especially on topics that are interesting, related to students’ daily life, and serving to reveal how physical laws are at work in the universe;
- comprehend the universality and powerfulness of the laws of physics, and their applications on a wide range of astronomical phenomena;
- apply thinking skills based on knowledge acquired in the study, and be able to solve basic problems in astronomy;
- comprehend and appreciate the beauty of the universe, and also the role played by astronomy in daily life;
- comprehend how a scientist approaches a problem, and applies the scientific methods to seek answers;
- express a critical mind by learning to confront beliefs with observations and evidence.

